definition.val: A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.
Temporal interval that defines human life from the prenatal stage until late adulthood.
Prenatal stage that starts with fertilization and ends with a fully formed embryo, before undergoing last development during the fetal stage.

comments: By embryo we mean in the sense of up to the 8th week postfertilization (over 7 and under 8 weeks), we treat fetus as a separate stage.

definition.val: Embryonic stage defined by a fertilized oocyte and presence of pronuclei.

comments: Starts at day 1 post-fertilization, beginning of the first week.

definition.val: Early stage of Carnegie stage 02 consisting of division of cells in the early embryo.
Embryonic stage during which cell division occurs with reduction in cytoplasmic volume, and formation of inner and outer cell mass.

comments: Usually starts between day 2 and day 3 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Embryonic stage that is an early stage of embryonic development in animals and is produced by cleavage of a fertilized ovum, with formation of a central fluid-filled cavity called the blastocoel.

comments: The blastula follows the morula and precedes the gastrula in the developmental sequence.

definition.val: Blastula stage with the loss of the zona pellucida and the definition of a free blastocyst.

comments: Usually starts between day 4 and day 5 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Blastula stage during which the blastocyst becomes attached.

comments: Usually starts between day 5 and day 6 post-fertilization.

basicPropertyValues.val: Note that GO treats blastocyst attachment and implantation (CS05) as synonymous

definition.val: Blastula stage during which implantation occurs.

comments: Usually starts between day 7 and day 12 post-fertilization, beginning of the second week.

definition.val: Embryonic stage defined by a complex and coordinated series of cellular movements that occurs at the end of cleavage.
Gastrula stage during which the extraembryonic mesoderm and primitive streak appear.

comments: Usually starts between day 13 and day 15 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Embryonic stage defined by the formation of a tube from the flat layer of ectodermal cells known as the neural plate.

comments: This stage starts the emergence of the central nervous system.

definition.val: Neurula stage during which the notochordal process appears, and gastrulation is continuing.

comments: Usually starts between day 15 and day 17 post-fertilization, beginning of the third week.

definition.val: Neurula stage during which the primitive pit and the notochordal canal appear.

comments: Usually starts between day 17 and day 19 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Embryonic stage at which the ectoderm, endoderm, and mesoderm develop into the internal organs of the organism.
Organogenesis stage during which somites 1-3 appear, and neural folds, cardiac primordium, and head fold are present.

comments: Usually starts between day 19 and day 21 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which somites 4-12 appear, and the neural fold fuses.

comments: Usually starts between day 22 and day 23 post-fertilization, beginning of the fourth week.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which somites 13-20 appear, and the rostral neuropore closes.

comments: Usually starts between day 23 and day 26 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which somites 21-29 appear, and the caudal neuropore closes.

comments: Usually starts between day 26 and day 30 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Organogenesis developmental stage during which somite 30 appears, and leg buds, lens placode, pharyngeal arches are present.

comments: Usually starts between day 28 and day 32 post-fertilization, beginning of the fifth week.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which lens pit and optic cup appear.

comments: Usually starts between day 31 and day 35 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which lens vesicle, nasal pit, and hand plate appear.

comments: Usually starts between day 35 and day 38 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which nasal pits moved ventrally, and features are auricular hillocks, and foot plate.

comments: Usually starts between day 37 and day 42 post-fertilization, beginning of the sixth week.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which finger rays become visible.

comments: Usually starts between day 42 and day 44 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which ossification commences.

comments: Usually starts between day 44 and day 48 post-fertilization, beginning of the seventh week.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which the straightening of the trunk starts.

comments: Usually starts between day 48 and day 51 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which upper limbs are longer and bent at elbow.

comments: Usually starts between day 51 and day 53 post-fertilization, beginning of the eighth week.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which hands and feet turned inward.

comments: Usually starts between day 53 and day 54 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which eyelids and external ears appear.

comments: Usually starts between day 54 and day 56 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Organogenesis stage during which the head, the body, and the limbs are rounded structures.

comments: Usually starts between day 56 and day 60 post-fertilization.

definition.val: Carnegie developmental stage 5 defined by a solid trophoblast.
Carnegie developmental stage 5 defined by a trophoblastic lacunae.
Carnegie developmental stage 5 defined by a lacunar vascular circle.
Carnegie developmental stage 6 during which chorionic villi appear.
Carnegie developmental stage 6 during which the primitive streak appears.
Prenatal stage that starts with the fully formed embryo and ends at birth.

comments: Prenatal development is a continuum, with no clear defining feature distinguishing an embryo from a fetus. The use of the term "fetus" generally implies that a mammalian embryo has developed to the point of being recognizable as belonging to its own species, though the point at which this occurs is subjective. [Wikipedia:Fetus]

definition.val: Prenatal stage that starts with fertilization and ends at birth.
Fetal stage when the fetus is over 8 and under 9 weeks of development.

comments: External genitalia begin to distinguish themselves as either male or female. Eyelids are completely closed, and vocal ligaments appear (see http://ehd.org/resources_bpd_documentation_english.php).

definition.val: Fetal stage when the fetus is over 9 and under 10 weeks of development.

comments: The fingernails and toenails begin to develop and unique fingerprints appear. Ossification is underway in most bones (see http://ehd.org/resources_bpd_documentation_english.php).

definition.val: Fetal stage when the fetus is over 10 and under 11 weeks of development.

comments: The nose and lips are completely formed, and external genitalia can be distinguished as male or female (see http://ehd.org/resources_bpd_documentation_english.php).

definition.val: Fetal stage when the fetus is over 11 and under 12 weeks of development.

comments: Upper limb length has nearly reached its final proportion to body size (see http://ehd.org/resources_bpd_documentation_english.php). The assignation of this week to the fourth or third LMP month is debatable (see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Prenatal_development_table.svg).

definition.val: Fetal stage when the fetus is over 12 and under 13 weeks of development.
Fetal stage when the fetus is over 13 and under 14 weeks of development.
Fetal stage when the fetus is over 14 and under 15 weeks of development.
Fetal stage when the fetus is over 15 and under 16 weeks of development.

comments: The assignation of this week to the fifth or fourth LMP month is debatable (see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Prenatal_development_table.svg).

definition.val: Fetal stage when the fetus is over 16 and under 17 weeks of development.
Fetal stage when the fetus is over 17 and under 18 weeks of development.
Fetal stage when the fetus is over 18 and under 19 weeks of development.
Fetal stage when the fetus is over 19 and under 20 weeks of development.

comments: The cochlea has reached adult size within the fully developed inner ear (see http://ehd.org/resources_bpd_documentation_english.php). The assignation of this week to the sixth or fifth LMP month is debatable (see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Prenatal_development_table.svg).

definition.val: Fetal stage when the fetus is over 20 and under 21 weeks of development.

comments: The lungs gain some ability to breathe air. This stage is considered the age of viability because survival outside the womb becomes possible for some fetuses (see http://ehd.org/resources_bpd_documentation_english.php).

definition.val: Fetal stage when the fetus is over 21 and under 22 weeks of development.
Fetal stage when the fetus is over 22 and under 23 weeks of development.
Fetal stage when the fetus is over 23 and under 24 weeks of development.

comments: The eyelids reopen (see http://ehd.org/resources_bpd_documentation_english.php).

definition.val: Fetal stage when the fetus is over 24 and under 25 weeks of development.

comments: The assignation of this week to the seventh or sixth LMP month is debatable (see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Prenatal_development_table.svg).

definition.val: Human developmental stage that covers the first period from birth, with breast feeding and/or bottled substitute, and that stops at language acquisition.

comments: The definition of an age for human weaning is difficult to define due to individual and cultural variations. The natural age of weaning in humans could be 2.5 years, with maximum 7.0 years (see https://www.health-e-learning.com/articles/A_Natural_Age_of_Weaning.pdf), but we decide to stop this period at 1 year-old, before usually language acquisition.

Defines the start and end of a stage with a duration of 1 month, relative to either the time of fertilization or last menstrual period of the mother (to be clarified), counting from one, in terms of a reference model. Thus if month_of_gestation=3, then the stage is 2 month in.
